Chapters 2²·34 (ἐξ 50-81 incl.) Kiihner regards as almost wholly taken from Plato. That Cicero had a work of Panaetius before him he thinks clear from ἐξ 42 and 78. That somebody (i Posidonius the pupil of Panaetius) had Panaetius before him seems clear from the present sections. The view of Heine which derives ἓξ 26-81 throughout from a Stoic source, and in fact from Posidonius, seems far more satisfactory. There seems to be very little in these sections that Posidonius might not have written if we except the Roman illustrations, and these are unusually few. I see no evidence to shew that in 3556& 5 Cicero may not have derived the basis of his arguments from Posidonius. Itis quite possible that Posidonius used the argument from Ἀνάμνησις, as Heine evidently thinks, but on the other hand he may not have accepted

this doctrine, and Cicero may have worked it in independently of his source.
